izardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=necridious>Necridious</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br>  Posts: 360<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/17/03 5:51 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Heal Like a Cleric</span><hr size=1> I've long been a supporter of better heals for both of the other 2 healer classes, though I've always felt that if Shaman and Druid need different heals, Shaman should get the better of the 2.<br>
<br>
This opinion does not come so much from the level 60+ perspective, but from the early levels.<br>
<br>
Untill level 29, Druids and Shaman recieved the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>exact</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> same healing spells in the same order as clerics did.  The clerical advantage came 3 ways: 10% bonus to healing spells for clerics, 10% penalty for everyone else(vi always fixes things twice), and the spells come one spell circle later.  With release, the Druids and SHaman got regen spells to make up their lack somewhat, and Shaman had the poorly understood and underused till the endgame slow spells.  Clerics got a HoT with Luclin to mirror their HoT line in the post 50's at like level 19.<br>
<br>
Then, for reasons known only to VI, at level 39 Shaman and Druids did not recieve the superior healing spell, yet clerics got a second healing spell---the all mighty Complete Heal.  Unlike many other &quot;game breaking&quot; abilities in game such as slow or mez, the implications of Complete Heal were immediatly obvious, and only the lack of insane HP mobs prevented CH chains from forming on the spot upon release.<br>
<br>
The reasoning for this was simple in it's own way:  Clerics were the supreme healers of the game, so got sole access to the best healing spell in the game- Superior Heal.  CH was not seen as a healing spell, but as a spell to remove downtime, thus the high mana cost and long cast time... it simply was not supposed to be a battle heal.  Would have been nice if VI would have owned up to the way CH was being used then, at the beginning and done something about it (can we say 1 min non stack timer and radical reduction in size, possibly draining all mana?).  The only real problem with this reasoning is that the game manual clearly described both shaman and clerics as primarily healers, with cleric secondary focus going to nukes, and shaman secondary ability going to augmentation and debuff.  The balance on druids is that they got both the healing, and good nukes, and servicable buffs if a cleric wasn't around.<br>
<br>
What should have happened, IMHO, is when Kunark got underway, and dungeon crawling became a serious bad time without a Cleric/Chanter/Tank combo, is to revisit and complete the healing line.  When the top level was 50, they probably thought Sup heal and Greater heal was enough.  However, it quickly became evident to anyone and everyone it was not.  Level 39 should have seen Sup heal for shamans and Druids, 44 should have seen Even_Bigger_Heal for clerics, with shaman and druids getting that at 49, and then at 54 clerics could have gotten a special cleric only heal---assuming the new Heal Over Time line wasn't considered special enough.  Remember that according to VI back then, level 50-60 was for special wing-dings on the classes, not core functions.  50-60 was supposed to see the power upgrade of a single level, not 10 levels.  This worked for the casters, but melee don't scale well that way apparently.<br>
<br>
So, for both Shaman and Druids, even today, I would see it as fair, if not needed, to move Sup Heal to level 39, and to continue the basic healing line through at least level 49, on the same curve it always  was on, so Even_Bigger Heal is probably right at 1k or a little better on healing, And Clerics could possibly get a 1.5k quick heal in the late 50's, possibly at 60.  This would simply be a continuation of the balance that exists pre 50 with the healing classes, and give people more options of healer post 50.  I've been in groups with a shaman and druid, and them saying we should get a 'healer'--and that's just wrong.<br>
 <p><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=448514">Antrygus Windrose </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=northyr>NOR Thyr</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/17/03 7:32 am)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Heal Like a Cleric</span><hr size=1> I consistently hear Druids asking for one of two things..either better heals or slows.<br>
<br>
Shamans are the ONLY priest class with slows.  In exchange for it, we (yes, we as in my main is a shaman) pay for it by having weaker heals than druids, crappier nukes than druids, and fewer types of DoT's then the necros we share our 2 DoT lines with.  Now, admittedly, at level 60 we get Torpor and at 65 we get Quiessence, two of the best Heal over Time spells in the game, however Torpor is so insanely rare that it isn't even funny, usually selling for 80-100k and only dropping rarely from Kunark Dragons and even more rarely from a few other mobs in Kunark.  Many shamans never get Torpor.<br>
<br>
As such Shamans are, without question, the best slowers in the game.  Our best slow is level 51 or 52, and has the best % of any slow in the game.  Additionally, we have better armor, better damage mitigation, and better hp than enchanters.  As healers though, our 75% CHeal is capped lower than Druids, and with the 100% snare and the 30%(ish) slow attached to Torpor, it's not effective for healing tanks during combat.<br>
<br>
Most shamans have generally accepted the fact that we are specialists in buffing/debuffing/slowing.  But Druids can't seem to accept that they AREN'T specialists.  Druids fit the bill of &quot;Jack of all trades, master of none&quot;.  If they want to be a specialist at something, they'd have to give up a LOT of abilities.  Wizards, for example, specialize in doing damage, as such we get no heals, virtually no buffs and what few buffs we have are of limited usefulness either being self only or single target.  Wizards have NO abilities pertinent to xp grouping/raiding aside from evaccing/porting and doing lots of DPS.<br>
<br>
Clerics heal and mitigate death.  And for the most part, that is all they do.  They have some buffs, but mostly hp/ac buffs (which make sense for a healer), they have some nukes, but their nukes have relatively poor mana/damage ratios.  Clerics cannot effectively or efficiently fill in for any other class.  They are a TRUE specialist.  IF you want Druids to be as good at healing or be able to mitigate death the way that Clerics do, and be fair to clerics in the process,then they'd have to give up EVERYTHING else they do..effectively BECOMING clerics.  Somehow, I don't see the druids who are asking for these changes wanting that, they just want to be given it all without giving up anything in the process.  <br>
<br>
Do they need better heals.. Maybe, but personally I don't think so, I've never had any difficulty in PoP groups with Druid main healers.  Do they *need* death mitigation to make them more groupable.. No, they may want it, but they don't NEED it. Do they need to heal or mitigate death as well as clerics..hell no.<br>
<br>
